                      <td style="vertical-align: top;">
                        <ul>
                          <li>Limited financial resources. They often have limited access to capital and are unable to secure loans or investment funding.</li>
                          <li>Limited staff and expertise. For small businesses, it can be challenging to hire and retain employees with the necessary skills and expertise to help the business grow.</li>
                          <li>Intense competition from larger businesses. Larger businesses often have more resources, such as financial, technological, and marketing resources, and may be able to offer similar products or services at a lower price point due to economies of scale.</li>
                          <li>Limited access to capital or funding. One of the major challenges faced by small businesses is limited access to capital or funding.</li>
                          <li>Difficulty in attracting and retaining top talent. Small businesses may find it challenging to attract and retain top talent due to a variety of factors.</li>
                          <li>High risk of failure, and the risk of failure is high, particularly in the early stages. Many new businesses fail within the first few years of operation due to various factors</li>
                          <li>Limited scalability and potential for growth can be a major challenge for small businesses. Scaling up a business is crucial for achieving long-term success, but small businesses often struggle to do so due to a variety of factors.</li>
                          <li>Difficulty in competing with larger businesses in terms of pricing, marketing, and distribution.Larger businesses often have the advantage of economies of scale, which allows them to produce goods or services at a lower cost per unit.</li>
                          <li>Limited access to resources such as technology, research, and development. Technology is constantly evolving, and businesses that lack access to the latest technologies may struggle to remain competitive.</li>
                          <li>Regulatory compliance and legal challenges. Regulatory compliance refers to the laws and regulations that a company must comply with in order to operate within the legal framework of the country or region where it operates.</li>
                          <li>Limited bargaining power with suppliers and vendors when it comes to negotiating with its suppliers and vendors. In other words, the business is at a disadvantage when it comes to setting terms and prices for the goods and services.</li>
